{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538579"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:30:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:30:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16254"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16254"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.58,0.06,0.22,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8945"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64516"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8945"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16254"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49948"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"960"},{"type":"tags","id":"2112"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4101"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43623"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64516"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of intermittent right-sided lower abdominal pain. The pain is dull in nature and not related to her menstrual cycle. She has no other symptoms. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications except for the combined oral contraceptive pill. She is sexually active with a regular partner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft with mild tenderness in the right iliac fossa. There is no rebound tenderness or guarding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA transvaginal ultrasound reveals a 6 cm right ovarian mass containing hyperechoic material, calcification, and a fluid-fluid level. The left ovary appears normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endometrioma","Dermoid cyst","Tubo-ovarian abscess","Serous cystadenoma","Corpus luteum cyst"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ultrasound findings in this case are highly characteristic of a \u003Cstrong\u003Edermoid cyst\u003C/strong\u003E (mature cystic teratoma). These benign ovarian tumours typically contain various tissue types derived from all three germ cell layers. On ultrasound, they classically appear as complex masses containing hyperechoic (fatty) material, calcification, and fluid-fluid levels. The patient\u0027s age and presentation with intermittent pain are also consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eendometrioma\u003C/strong\u003E typically appears as a homogeneous, hypoechoic cyst with low-level internal echoes, often described as having a \u0027ground glass\u0027 appearance. Additionally, endometriomas are usually associated with cyclical pain and other symptoms of endometriosis, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorpus luteum cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is a functional ovarian cyst that develops after ovulation. It typically appears as a thin-walled cyst with peripheral vascularity on ultrasound and usually resolves spontaneously within a few menstrual cycles. The complex appearance with calcification would be unusual for a corpus luteum cyst.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eserous cystadenoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically appears as a unilocular cyst with thin septations and would not contain the characteristic hyperechoic material or calcification seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etubo-ovarian abscess\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with acute pain, fever, and elevated inflammatory markers. On ultrasound, it appears as a complex multiloculated mass with thick walls and internal echoes, often with surrounding inflammation. The patient\u0027s well appearance and lack of systemic symptoms make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDermoid cysts are the most common germ cell tumours of the ovary, accounting for approximately 20% of all ovarian neoplasms. They are typically found in women of reproductive age. While many are asymptomatic and discovered incidentally, they can cause intermittent pain due to torsion or mass effect. Surgical removal is often recommended due to the risk of torsion and rupture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dermoid cysts typically appear on ultrasound as complex masses containing fat, calcification, and solid components.","Dermoid cysts are the most common germ cell tumour of the ovary, typically occurring in women of reproductive age.","Most dermoid cysts are asymptomatic and found incidentally, but can cause intermittent pain due to torsion."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Management of suspected ovarian masses in premenopausal women (Green-top Guideline No. 62) [Internet]. London: RCOG; 2011 [cited 2024 Nov 23]. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/guidance/browse-all-guidance/green-top-guidelines/ovarian-masses-in-premenopausal-women-management-of-suspected-green-top-guideline-no-62/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49948"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16254"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49948"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T18:58:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T18:59:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8945"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64516"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/960"},"attributes":{"emo